**Instructions**
I created an api project with asp.net core 2.1 and ef core 2.1. 
Using the browser refresh request caused the memory to rise!

**Functional impact**
Memory from about 30mb after the start of the project, has been up to about 1.x gb, this will lead to memory leaks?

**Minimal repro steps**
1. Create asp.net core 2.1 api project
```csharp
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web">

  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFramework>netcoreapp2.1</TargetFramework>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <ItemGroup>
    <Folder Include="wwwroot\" />
  </ItemGroup>

  <ItemGroup>
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.AspNetCore.App" />
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.SqlServer" Version="2.1.0" />
  </ItemGroup>

</Project>
```
2. Create a book entity
```csharp
using System;
using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations;

namespace EfCoreTest
{
    /// <summary>
    /// book info
    /// </summary>
    public class Book
    {
        public const int MaxNameLength = 50;

        /// <summary>
        /// primary key
        /// </summary>
        [Key]
        public virtual int Id { get; set; }

        /// <summary>
        /// book name
        /// </summary>
        [Required]
        [MaxLength(MaxNameLength)]
        public virtual string Name { get; set; }

        /// <summary>
        /// creation time
        /// </summary>
        public virtual DateTime CreationTime { get; set; }
    }
}
```
3. Create a dbcontext
```csharp
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;

namespace EfCoreTest.Repository
{
    public class EfCoreDbContext : DbContext
    {
        public EfCoreDbContext(DbContextOptions<EfCoreDbContext> options) : base(options)
        {
        }

        /// <summary>
        /// book dbset
        /// </summary>
        public DbSet<Book> Books { get; set; }
    }
}
```
4. Create a book service API
```csharp
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using EfCoreTest.Repository;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;

namespace EfCoreTest.Controllers
{
    /// <summary>
    /// book api service
    /// </summary>
    [Route("api/[controller]")]
    [ApiController]
    public class BooksController : ControllerBase
    {
        private readonly DbContext _context;

        /// <summary>
        /// </summary>
        public BooksController(EfCoreDbContext context)
        {
            _context = context;
        }

        /// <summary>
        /// test to get some books
        /// </summary>
        [HttpGet]
        public async Task<List<Book>> Get()
        {
            var query = _context.Set<Book>().AsQueryable();
            return await query.Take(1000).ToListAsync();
        }
    }
}
```

After starting the project, constantly refresh the browser access address: api/books, check the dotnet process, you will find that the memory has been rising, and will not be recycled in the short term.

**Question**
Is this normal?
Will it cause a memory leak?

Thanks in advance to the .net core team for answering my questions. Thank you!

